hreat-actor interaction remain hard blocks, but source-level approval/legal/status gaps should surface as metadata-only review or queue states with victim/company, claimed accounts, dataset size, actor statement/description, provenance, hashes, and allowed-field visibility. - Every extracted claim must preserve provenance: source id, capture id, URL/channel, collection timestamp, content hash, extractor version, and confidence. - Analyst-loop persistence is reserved for safe workflow metadata only: collection plans/runs/tasks, metadata review tasks, victim-notification packets, and claim ledger entries. These records may contain company/victim, affected-account counts or descriptions, dataset-size claims, actor statement summaries, hashes, provenance, and allowed actions, but must never contain raw leaked rows, credential values, private access material, downloaded datasets, or actor-interaction transcripts. - `src/types.ts` now owns the shared analyst-loop persistence contracts (`AnalystMetadataReviewTask`, `AnalystSourceActivationPacket`, `AnalystVictimNotificationPacket`, `AnalystClaimLedgerEntry`, and `AnalystLoopSnapshot`). Storage implementations should persist these shapes exactly and keep restricted/leak data metadata-only. - `/v1/analyst/metadata-review-tasks` is the route-visible metadata review inbox for leak/threat-actor claims. It may list safe metadata, claim ledger entries, redacted notification packets, and dry-run/explicit analyst action results only; it must never deliver notifications, fetch restricted targets, activate sources silently, or expose raw leaked material. - `/v1/analyst/loop` is the persisted analyst-loop read model for `/ti` and analyst consoles. It should replay the latest metadata-only loop snapshot plus review tasks, activation packets, notification drafts, and claim-ledger entries by tenant/query/run without rerunning collection. It must preserve the same `queued`, `metadata_review`, `blocked_unsafe_target`, `needs_source_activation`, and `ready` semantics and no-leak guarantees as `/v1/intel/search.analystLoop`. - `/v1/analyst/source-activation-packets` is the operator/legal approval queue for metadata-only source activation packets. Packet rows should include an `approvalWorkflow` object with the requested source/action, approval requirement, expected metadata-only effect, rollback, allowed operator actions, forbidden operations, and no-mutation/no-crawl delivery boundary. It may record explicit dry-run approval metadata on packets, but it must never mutate source status, enqueue crawling, enable restricted fetches, or bypass raw leak/download/credential/private-access blocks. - `/v1/analyst/source-activation-packets/{id}/execution-preview` is the safe downstream handoff packet for operator/legal source restore decisions. It may expose source id, approval state, prerequisites, expected metadata-only effect, rollback, `approvalWorkflow`, and forbidden operations; it must never activate a source, enqueue collection, enable restricted fetches, or convert blocked unsafe targets into runnable work. - `/v1/analyst/victim-notification-packets` is the redacted victim/company notification packet queue. Packet rows should include the same UI-ready `claimHeadline` and explicit `verificationBoundary` as metadata-review rows plus a `redactedNotification` object with claimed victim/company, affected accounts, dataset size, actor statement summary, timestamps, confidence, source hash/provenance, redactions, and "what was not accessed" text so company notification handoffs preserve "metadata only, not verified/downloaded" context. It may approve, cancel, or record externally sent notifications, but the scraper must never deliver notifications itself or expose raw leaked data, credentials, unsafe URLs, private-access material, or actor-interaction transcripts. - `/v1/analyst/victim-notification-packets/{id}/export` is the safe downstream handoff packet for approved external company-notification workflows.